y believing that nuclear weapons would compel the international community to engage on his terms with no such prospect in sight north korea faces a multitude of intractable problems will north koreans accept his son as their leader and will he embrace new thinking to solve the country's problems why do north korean leaders resist reform of an economic system that impoverishes the people can a country so dependent on outside help continue to defy the international community in troubled transition leading international experts examine these dilemmas offering new insights into how a troubled north korea may evolve in light of the ways other command economies and totalitarian states from the soviet union and east germany to vietnam and china have transitioned topics china germany north korea russia vietnam search aparc search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest north korea and identity politics in south korea gi wook shin kristin c burke brown journal of world affairs vol 15 1 2008 pdf+ cover changing relations between party military and government in north korea and their impact on policy direction jinwook choi shorenstein aparc 1999 pdf+ forgotten lessons of helsinki human rights and us north korean relations john feffer world policy journal vol xxi 2004 pdf+ cover politics of nationalism in us korean relations the gi wook shin paul yunsik chang asian perspective vol 28 2004 cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 9741 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
